Sure! Here's an example of how you can automatically generate a table of contents (TOC) in a LaTeX document using the `tableofcontents` package:

First, add the `tableofcontents` package to your LaTeX document's preamble:
```
\documentclass{book}
\usepackage{tableofcontents}
```
Next, add the following code to your document's preamble to generate the TOC:
```
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Section 1}
\section{Section 2}
\chapter{Chapter 2}
\section{Section 3}
\section{Section 4}

\end{document}
```
This will generate a table of contents with the following structure:

* Introduction
	+ Section 1
	+ Section 2
* Chapter 2
	+ Section 3
	+ Section 4

You can customize the appearance of the TOC by adjusting the formatting options provided by the `tableofcontents` package. For example, you can change the font size, font style, and color of the TOC entries by adding the following commands to your preamble:
```
\renewcommand\cftchapterfont{\Large\bfseries}
\renewcommand\cftsectionfont{\normalsize\em}
\setcounter{tocdepth}{3}
```
This will change the font size and style of the chapter and section headings in the TOC, and set the depth of the TOC to 3 levels (so that only chapters and sections are displayed, but not subsections).

Note that you can also use other packages, such as `hyperref`, to create a clickable table of contents that links to the corresponding sections in your document.

